<br>
While some may not think its fair, the operating principles The Grubs try to adhere to are based on our understanding of Mith Marr's protocol: first to mobilize with sufficient force engages and kills uber-mob.<br>
<br>
Anything else removes the &quot;game&quot; element.  After all, part of the game is competition.  It should, however, be as fair as possible and that's where it gets messy.  The major problem with the RF spawn (and others like it if they exist) is that the word &quot;engage&quot; is left open to intrepretation.<br>
<br>
Is kiting with the intent of occupying the mob while forces mobilize engaging?<br>
<br>
Is aggro'ing a mob and then FD'ing over and over again with the intent of occupying the mob engaging?<br>
<br>
Is charming a mob repeatedly with the intent of occupying a mob engaging?<br>
<br>
The answer to this IMHO is no.  Yes, both guilds involved did some of the above.  They were forced to due to the mob's design.  Re-read Ronadrum's suggestions.  Make the mob uncharmable, faster than any player speed, rooted, whatever.  Make it so that once you've &quot;engaged&quot; the mob there is no doubt there is intent to kill.<br>
<br>
Taken to the extreme, the current rules VI has when placed against the RF spawn can result in what others have referred to: one player gets aggro first and then has unlimited time to gather forces to take the mob down?  That's crazy.  VI's intent with the &quot;first to get aggro, owns spawn&quot; was based upon the assumption that the multiple parties involved were all actively trying to &quot;engage&quot; in a killing melee.<br>
<br>
I guess my point is, more guidance from VI is truly required here.  Other's have quipped that people should just &quot;work it out&quot;.  We all know that ambiguity breeds conflict.  VI needs to fix the game mechanics to minimize/avoid these types of scenarios. <p><HR width="50%"><b><FONT COLOR="GREEN"><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13607">Greythan Aetherion</A></FONT></b><BR>
